land":"Kent, England","Whitchurch, Cheshire, England":"Whitchurch, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Avington, England":"Avington, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clarke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Clark  .","History: This name was brought independently to New England by many bearers from the 17th century onward. Nicholas Clarke was one of the founders of Hartford, CT (coming from Cambridge, MA with Thomas Hooker) in 1635."],"variants":[{"name":"Clark","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>clerk</i>, <i>clark</i> ‘clerk, cleric, writer’ (Old French <i>clerc</i>; see   Clerc  ). The original sense was ‘man in a religious order, cleric, clergyman’. As all writing and secretarial work in medieval Christian Europe was normally done by members of the clergy, the term <i>clerk</i> came to mean ‘scholar, secretary, recorder, or penman’ as well as ‘cleric’. As a surname, it was particularly common for one who had taken only minor holy orders. In medieval Christian Europe, clergy in minor orders were permitted to marry and so found families; thus the surname could become established.","Irish (Westmeath, Mayo): in Ireland the English surname was frequently adopted, partly by translation for <i>Ó Cléirigh</i>; see   Cleary  .","Americanized form of Dutch   De Klerk   or Flemish   De Clerck   or of variants of these names, and possibly also of French   Clerc  . Compare   Clerk   2 and   De Clark  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas M Clarke was born on 25 December 1220, in Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Edward Clarke II, was 30 and his mother, Mary Coningsby, was 30. He married Lady Angharad de Malpas in 1253, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. He died on 3 July 1273, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52."},"et":{"25 December 1220–3 July 1273":"25. detsember 1220–3. juuli 1273","1220–1273":"1220–1273","1225–1279":"1225–1279","1242–1266":"1242–1266","1242–1280":"1242–1280","1253–1302":"1253–1302","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1190":"1190","July 1273":"juuli 1273","1242":"1242","1253":"1253","1220":"1220","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","1302":"1302","1225":"1225","1279":"1279","1266":"1266","3 July 1273":"3. juuli 1273","25 December 1220":"25. detsember 1220","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Whitchurch, Cheshire, England":"Whitchurch, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Avington, England":"Avington, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"25 December 1220–3 July 1273":"25. joulukuuta 1220–3. heinäkuuta 1273","1220–1273":"1220–1273","1225–1279":"1225–1279","1242–1266":"1242–1266","1242–1280":"1242–1280","1253–1302":"1253–1302","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1190":"1190","July 1273":"heinäkuu 1273","1242":"1242","1253":"1253","1220":"1220","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1280":"1280","1302":"1302","1225":"1225","1279":"1279","1266":"1266","3 July 1273":"3. heinäkuuta 1273","25 December 1220":"25. joulukuuta 1220","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Whitchurch, Cheshire, England":"Whitchurch, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Avi